Explanation:

The documents describe Washington-on-the-Brazos as the first capital of the Republic of Texas (file_path: /Users/stefanomarchesin/Research/fshami/Rag/docs/dbpedia_9283/re-ranker-msmarco/29.txt) and later confirm that it was also the second capital, after Harrisburg on Buffalo Bayou was used as a temporary capital (file_path: /Users/stefanomarchesin/Research/fshami/Rag/docs/dbpedia_9283/re-ranker-msmarco/13.txt). Additionally, one of the documents states that Washington-on-the-Brazos served as the last capital of the Republic of Texas from 1842-1845 (file_path: /Users/stefanomarchesin/Research/fshami/Rag/docs/dbpedia_9283/re-ranker-msmarco/55.txt). Therefore, based on the information provided in the documents, it is correct that Washington-on-the-Brazos was a capital of the Republic of Texas.

qwen2.5.reason: The context states that while Washington-on-the-Brazos was the first capital of the Republic of Texas, it served as such for only a brief period from March 1, 1836, until March 1842. After this, the capital moved to Harrisburg and then to nearer-to-Austin locations before Austin became the permanent capital in 1846.
